hondo717: |cp||at|ok, this was a very good example of a common advanced declarer play technique known as a "strip and end play." When when aggie is in with the K of clubs, she is stuck. If she leads a club or a heart, elizabeth can sluff her losing diamond from her hand, and ruff in dummy. If aggie leads a diamond, as she did, then elizabeth can play for split honors, and eliminate the diamond loser. The idea is, if elizabeth plays diamonds herself, she will lose a diamond and a club, and be down 1. But by eliminating all the side suits from both hands (stripping both hands), and throwing us in, she makes one of us give her the extra trick she needs to make the hand.|
