nt||bt||mn|        Control Bids - Howard Schutzman        |
ht|e|at|^b@2Control bids are a method some experts use as a way of exploring for slam. They are used to discover if the partnership @E@3has first and/or second round control of the non-trump suit. First round control means the partnership can capture the first trick in the suit (e.g. someone has the ace or a void in the suit). Second round control means the partnership can capture the second trick in the suit (e.g. someone has the king or a singleton in the suit). To bid a small slam, you need first round control of at least 3 suits and second round control of the remaining suit. To bid a grand slam, you need first round control of all suits.

A control bidding sequence is initiated once a partnership has established a game forcing auction and has agreed upon a trump suit. For example, in the sequence |HT|M|CS|1|at|^H {|ia|1hp2np3hp4c|at|}     4@C is a control bid, showing |HT|N|AT|^Sa control in clubs.|HT|Q|AT|^B
Italian control bids are the simplest and most effective way to play control bids. With Italian control bids, the first time a suit is bid, the bidder is guaranteeing either first or second round control in that suit. Also, if the bidder skips a suit, the bidder is denying a control in that suit. So, in the example auction above, the 4@C bid shows first or second round control of clubs, and denies first or second round control of spades.|

