nt||bt||mn|        Control Bids - Howard Schutzman        |

ht|e|at|^b@2Italian control bids allow the partnership to quickly discover if they lack control of one suit, and stop at game. For @E@3instance, in the example auction, if the partner of the 4@C bidder does not have a control in spades, he should stop in 4@H, because slam is not possible.

Italian control bids work well in conjunction with Roman Key Card Blackwood. The partnership can usually establish if they have first or second round control in all side suits below the level of 4N. Once control of all side suits is established, 4N can then be used to determine if the partnership has enough key cards to warrant bidding slam. This is typically how Italian control bids are used.

On rare occasions, the partnership may want to skip Roman Key Card Blackwood, particularly if one member of the partnership has strong enough trumps so that he knows there are no trump losers. In that case, the control bidding sequence can continue beyond 4N. Bidding a suit the second time (by either partner, even if the other partner bid the suit first) shows first round control of the suit. The partnership should only skip Blackwood if they know there are no trump losers.

Many experts play a slightly different method of control bids. They play that the first time a suit is bid, it guarantees first round control of the suit. The advantage of this method is that the control bid is less ambiguous. However, the disadvantages are that it is easy for the partnership to get too high before discovering they lack controls in one suit, and it is often not possible to use Roman Key Card Blackwood once a control bidding sequence is initiated. Therefore, I recommend that partnerships use the Italian control bid approach.

Another term some people use for control bid is "cue bid". However, cue bids are also used for many other purposes, such as Michaels, showing a limit raise or better in partner's suit, and asking for a stopper. Control bid is a more precise term.|
